  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@Vru{{}}@HI{{@EM{{wakenihaikanai}}}} would be inappropriate in the following sentence as it expresses a simple inability.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{me}}ha@KT{{piano}}ga@KJ{{bullet}}kenai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I cannot play the piano. <em>(I do not know how to play the piano).</em>
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
This sentence, however, indicates that the speaker is not able to play the piano because of some external circumstance,
for example it is late at night. It is in fact likely that the speaker does know how to play the piano.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{me}}ha@KT{{piano}}ga@KJ{{bullet}}ku@EM{{wakenihaikanai}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I cannot play the piano <em>(owing to external circumstances).</em>
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="no-choice">@Vnai{{}}@HI{{@EM{{wakenihaikanai}}}}</a> is used by the speaker to indicate that there is no choice other than to do something.

<table class="sentence">
